I remember reading how some old school powerlifters used to go to the buffet and eat a ton while drinking beer after a session. I think Mike Mentzer or some other HIT bodybuilder said he and his training partners went to the bar and also had a few beers after heavy duty workouts.

Then in Arnold Schwarzenegger's first gym they just drank beer during the barbell sessions for fuel and hydration, it was common practice. It really just doesn't matter. Unless you're an actual alcoholic or malnourished on zero animal protein it really just doesn't do anything.

You can't have direct knowledge of abstractions and hypotheticals, instruments of calculations, or verbal symbols. In Orthodox Christianity the word "theology" is associated with theosis, as in a saint having direct experience with the divine and transmitting knowledge to others.

Evola talks about this in "The Yoga of Power", but in traditional Hindu philosophy there was no abstraction or conceptual speculation, just a practitioner in a high spiritual state giving you his literal "point of view", like a guy telling you what he's seeing from up in a tree.

Basically you just have to send a guy up to Heaven and then have him tell you what he saw up there afterwards. Like a mountain climber describing the view from the top of a peak or a scout. And you trust him to be saying the truth. And the guy is an Orthodox saint in the example.
